---
import DocsLayout from '../../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import StepList from '../../../../components/StepList.astro';
import Callout from '../../../../components/Callout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Step-by-step guide" description="Your first project walkthrough, ticket by ticket.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Project 1: Step-by-Step Guide</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">This guide walks you through your first project. By the end, you'll have a live website at a real URL that you directed AI to build.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Before You Start</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Complete the <a href="/web-dev/getting-started">Web Dev setup</a> first. You need all tools installed and verified.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-6">Then read through the project materials. Here's what each one is and why it matters:</p>

  <div class="space-y-4 mb-8">
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-primary bg-primary-bg p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1"><a href="/web-dev/projects/1/prd">Product Requirements Document (PRD)</a></p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">The PRD defines <em>what</em> we're building — features, acceptance criteria, and crucially, what we're <em>not</em> building (anti-scope). In this project, the PRD has been written for you. In later projects, you'll direct AI to generate PRDs from client briefs — turning a vague conversation into a structured specification. For now, read the whole thing. Pay special attention to the anti-scope section.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-primary bg-primary-bg p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Architecture <span class="text-text-muted font-normal">(skipped in this project)</span></p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">In later projects, you'll direct AI to create an architecture document from the PRD — database schema, API contracts, component structure, and technology choices. The architecture is how you go from "what to build" to "how to build it." Project 1 is a simple static site, so we skip this step — but from Project 2 onwards, architecture becomes a key part of your planning.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-primary bg-primary-bg p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1"><a href="/web-dev/projects/1/backlog">Backlog</a></p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">The backlog is the list of tickets — small, ordered units of work with specific acceptance criteria. In later projects, you'll direct AI to break the architecture into tickets. In this project, the backlog has been written for you. Each ticket becomes one cycle of the loop: branch → build → verify → merge.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-primary bg-primary-bg p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1"><a href="/web-dev/projects/1/design">Design specification</a></p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">The design spec defines <em>how it looks</em> — colours, fonts, spacing, layout. This is what you verify AI's output against using browser DevTools. Specific values, not vibes.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-primary bg-primary-bg p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1"><a href="/web-dev/projects/1/claude-md">CLAUDE.md</a></p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">The project memory file. Claude Code reads this at the start of every session — it contains the tech stack, repo structure, anti-scope rules, and engineering standards. You paste this into your project so Claude stays consistent across sessions. In later projects, you'll direct AI to generate this from templates.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Setting Up</h2>

  <Callout variant="warning">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>GitHub permissions:</strong> Claude Code will need to create repositories, Issues, and PRs on your behalf. The first time it tries, your terminal may prompt you to authorise GitHub access. Follow the prompts — this is normal. If you run into issues, make sure <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">gh auth status</code> shows you're logged in.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Step 1: Create a directory and start Claude</h3>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ mkdir greenscape && cd greenscape
$ claude`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-6">Claude Code starts. You're now talking to your AI developer.</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3">Step 2: Direct Claude to set up the project</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-2">Paste the CLAUDE.md and BACKLOG.md content, then tell Claude. You can copy both from their pages — use the copy buttons on the <a href="/web-dev/projects/1/claude-md">CLAUDE.md</a> and <a href="/web-dev/projects/1/backlog">Backlog</a> pages.</p>
  <CodeBlock copy>{`I'm starting a new project. Here's the CLAUDE.md for the project:

[Paste the entire contents of CLAUDE.md here]

And here's the BACKLOG.md:

[Paste the entire contents of BACKLOG.md here]

Please start Ticket 1: Project Setup.

Create a new GitHub repository called "greenscape", initialise it with the CLAUDE.md and BACKLOG.md files, create the GitHub labels (setup, frontend, deploy), create Issues for all tickets in the backlog, and create a Project board with columns: To Do, In Progress, Done.`}</CodeBlock>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Step 3: Verify</h3>
  <StepList steps={[
    { title: "Open GitHub in your browser", content: "Navigate to your new repository." },
    { title: "Check the Issues tab", content: "You should see 8 Issues (one per ticket)." },
    { title: "Check the Projects tab", content: "You should see a board with all Issues in 'To Do'." },
    { title: "Open VS Code", content: "Open the greenscape folder. You should see CLAUDE.md and BACKLOG.md." },
  ]} />

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Ticket 1 complete.</strong> You directed Claude to set up project infrastructure and verified the result. The skill here was communication: clear instructions and verification against specific expectations.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-12">Your First Full Ticket Cycle (Ticket 2)</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-6">Now the real loop: branch → direct Claude → PR → review → merge.</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3">Step 1: Tell Claude to start the ticket</h3>
  <CodeBlock copy>{`Start Ticket 2: Development Environment.

Create a branch, set up the React + Vite project with Tailwind CSS, create the Makefile, create the content data file, and when done open a PR.`}</CodeBlock>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Step 2: Verify it works</h3>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2">In a new terminal tab:</p>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ cd greenscape
$ make dev`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">Open <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">localhost:5173</code>. Check each acceptance criterion from the backlog.</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Step 3: Read the reviews and merge</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-2">Read Claude's self-review and the Gemini review on the PR. If everything passes:</p>
  <CodeBlock copy>{`Everything looks good. Merge it.`}</CodeBlock>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>That's one complete ticket cycle.</strong> You'll repeat this for every ticket: direct → verify → review → merge.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-12">Continuing Through the Tickets</h2>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Ticket 3: Site Layout & Navigation</h3>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong>Your verification focus:</strong> Does the header look right? Use DevTools (F12) to check fonts and colours. On mobile (DevTools → toggle device toolbar), does the nav become a hamburger?</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Ticket 4: Hero & Services</h3>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong>Your verification focus:</strong> Count the service cards — exactly 6? Check the responsive grid: 1 → 2 → 3 columns as the viewport widens.</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Ticket 5: Testimonials & About</h3>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong>Your verification focus:</strong> Exactly 4 testimonials? Quotes in quotation marks? Star ratings are visual, not text? About text not too wide on desktop?</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Ticket 6: Service Area & Contact</h3>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong>Your verification focus:</strong> All 10 suburbs? <strong>Critical anti-scope check:</strong> did Claude add a contact form? The PRD says no forms — only phone and email links. Test the phone link on your phone.</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Ticket 7: SEO & Meta Tags</h3>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong>Your verification focus:</strong> Right-click → View Page Source. Search for <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">&lt;meta name="description"</code> and <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">og:title</code>. Run Lighthouse (DevTools → Lighthouse tab) — SEO score 90+?</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Ticket 8: Deploy</h3>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong>Your verification focus:</strong> Open the live URL on your phone. Does everything work? Phone link? Images? Run Lighthouse on the live URL.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-12">After You Finish</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Ask yourself: Did Claude add anything not in the PRD? Did I catch it? What was confusing? What felt natural?</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong>Show someone.</strong> Open the live URL on your phone. Say: "I directed AI to build this."</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Common Issues</h2>

  <details class="mb-3 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>"make dev doesn't work"</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Is Node.js installed? Run <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">node --version</code>. Are dependencies installed? Run <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">npm install</code>. Are you in the right directory? Run <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">pwd</code>.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
  <details class="mb-3 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>"Claude can't create the GitHub repo"</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Run <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">gh auth status</code>. If not logged in, run <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">gh auth login</code>.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
  <details class="mb-3 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>"The site looks different from the design"</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">That's normal — it's your job to catch the differences. Use DevTools to compare specific values (font size, colours, spacing). Direct Claude to fix: "The heading is 18px but should be 24px per the design."</p>
    </div>
  </details>
  <details class="mb-3 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>"Claude added something not in the PRD"</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">This is expected and educational. AI does this constantly. Direct Claude: "The PRD anti-scope says no [feature]. Remove it." This is the most important skill you're learning.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
  <details class="mb-3 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>"The deploy failed"</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Read the error message. Copy it. Paste to Claude: "The deploy failed with this error: [paste]. Fix it." You don't fix it — you communicate the error and direct the fix.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
</DocsLayout>
